hands_on_practices.problem:
In spectrometric identification of organic compounds, the ¹³C Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) chemical shift $\delta$ of the carbonyl carbon in aromatic aldehydes reflects its electronic environment via magnetic shielding. Electron-withdrawing substituents generally reduce shielding, shifting $\delta$ downfield (larger $\delta$), whereas electron-donating substituents increase shielding, shifting $\delta$ upfield (smaller $\delta$). The Hammett substituent constant $\sigma$ provides a well-tested, quantitative measure of the electron-withdrawing or electron-donating character of substituents on an aromatic ring, and Linear Free-Energy Relationships (LFERs) are widely used to correlate substituent effects with observables. Assume a linear Hammett-type correlation for the ¹³C carbonyl chemical shift of para-substituted benzaldehydes of the form
$$
\delta_i = \delta_0 + \rho\,\sigma_i,
$$
where $\delta_i$ is the observed ¹³C chemical shift of the carbonyl carbon for compound $i$, $\sigma_i$ is the para Hammett substituent constant for the substituent in compound $i$, $\delta_0$ is the intercept corresponding to the unsubstituted reference, and $\rho$ is the reaction constant quantifying sensitivity of $\delta$ to $\sigma$. The least-squares estimate of $\rho$ is defined by minimizing the sum of squared residuals.

You are provided the following experimentally observed data for para-substituted benzaldehydes $\text{p-X-C}_6\text{H}_4\text{CHO}$, with $X \in \{\text{NO}_2, \text{CN}, \text{CF}_3, \text{Cl}, \text{H}, \text{CH}_3, \text{OCH}_3\}$:
- $\text{NO}_2$: $\sigma_p = 0.78$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 195.4$ ppm;
- $\text{CN}$: $\sigma_p = 0.66$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 195.0$ ppm;
- $\text{CF}_3$: $\sigma_p = 0.54$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 194.6$ ppm;
- $\text{Cl}$: $\sigma_p = 0.23$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 193.4$ ppm;
- $\text{H}$: $\sigma_p = 0.00$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 192.6$ ppm;
- $\text{CH}_3$: $\sigma_p = -0.17$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 191.9$ ppm;
- $\text{OCH}_3$: $\sigma_p = -0.27$, $\delta(\text{C}=O) = 191.6$ ppm.

Using the least-squares criterion starting from first principles, determine the best-fit value of $\rho$ in the linear model above. Then, based on the sign and magnitude of the fitted $\rho$, briefly interpret the electronic effect of the substituents on the carbonyl carbon’s ¹³C chemical shift within the Hammett framework.

Express the final numerical value of $\rho$ in ppm per Hammett unit, and round your answer to four significant figures. Do not include units in your final boxed answer.
